This article is a statement made by President Obama in 2013 addressing the issue of obstruction in Congress. The President expresses his frustration with the pattern of obstruction that has prevented important legislation from being passed and well-qualified individuals from filling critical positions. He highlights specific examples of legislation that has been blocked, such as job creation, equal pay for women, immigration reform, and gun control measures. The President also discusses the obstruction of his judicial nominees, emphasizing that this gridlock in Congress is causing problems in the justice system. He supports a change in Senate rules to restore the tradition of considering nominations on a more routine basis. The President believes that the American people deserve better than politicians who hinder the functioning of government and expresses hope that the change in Senate rules will lead to more bipartisan work and progress.